{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d81cdafb-9398-4ddc-9f26-3669254a41d3","content":"## The Problem\n\n**.NET MAUI's Android build ignores `JAVA_HOME`.** It uses its own MSBuild property `$(JavaSdkDirectory)` to locate the JDK, so even though `java -version` works, the build can't find your JDK.\n\n## Fix Options\n\n**Option 1** — Tell MSBuild where your JDK is. Add to your `.csproj` (or `Directory.Build.props`):\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup Condition=\"$([MSBuild]::IsOSPlatform('osx'))\">\n  <JavaSdkDirectory>/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/temurin-17.jdk/Contents/Home</JavaSdkDirectory>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n**Option 2** — Pass it on the command line:\n\n```bash\ndotnet build -p:JavaSdkDirectory=\"/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/temurin-17.jdk/Contents/Home\"\n```\n\n**Option 3** — Install Microsoft's OpenJDK (auto-discovered by the tooling):\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload install android\n```\n\nThis installs Microsoft's OpenJDK 17 to a path the build tools find automatically (`~/Library/Developer/Xamarin/jdk/`).\n\n---\n\n**Verify your path is correct** — on macOS, Adoptium installs under `/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/temurin-17.jdk/Contents/Home`. Make sure that's where `JAVA_HOME` and any `JavaSdkDirectory` point (the `Contents/Home` suffix is required).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"bc30cbb8-b139-4d43-af5b-0ce301fe3274","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is on macOS with a .NET MAUI Android build failing with a Java-related error. They have Adoptium Temurin JDK 17.0.12 installed and JAVA_HOME points to it.\n\nThe common issue here is that .NET MAUI / Android SDK build tools require a specific JDK version. Let me think about what's likely wrong:\n\n1. .NET MAUI (especially newer versions like .NET 8+) requires JDK 17, which they have.\n2. However, a very common issue on macOS with Adoptium Temurin is the **path structure**. \n\nOn macOS, Adoptium installs to `/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/temurin-17.jdk/Contents/Home/` and JAVA_HOME needs to point to the `Contents/Home` directory specifically. Beyond that, .NET's Android SDK has its own MSBuild property that can override JAVA_HOME entirely, potentially pointing to a different JDK location. The most likely culprit though is a version mismatch—.NET 8 and later have stricter JDK requirements that might not be satisfied even with JDK 17 installed if the build tools aren't finding it correctly. set correctly to include `/Contents/Home`. The real issue is likely that JAVA_HOME isn't pointing to the right location, or the .NET build tools are bypassing it entirely and looking for Microsoft's OpenJDK distribution instead. Without seeing the exact error message, the most probable culprits are either a version mismatch between what .NET 9 expects and what's installed, or a path resolution problem specific to how the Android workload discovers the JDK. The user likely has .NET 9 or 10, and the real culprit is probably that .NET MAUI isn't respecting their JAVA_HOME environment variable—it's looking for its own `JavaSdkDirectory` instead. On macOS specifically, the path needs to include `/Contents/Home` at the end, so it should point to `/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/temurin-17.jdk/Contents/Home` rather than just the root JDK folder. The real problem is that .NET MAUI's Android build doesn't use `JAVA_HOME` — it looks for the JDK through its own `JavaSdkDirectory` MSBuild property instead. I can fix this by either setting that property directly in the project file or as an environment variable for the dotnet command.\n\nBut wait, I should also consider whether the JDK version itself is the issue. If they're on .NET 10 in April 2026, it might actually require JDK 21 rather than JDK 17, which would explain why the build is failing even though Java is installed and working.","outputTokens":2156,"requestId":"083E:DE08:A8AB30:C25B15:69F2A847"},"id":"a8c7c3ad-a0f3-4a25-91ce-8392f2c2013f","timestamp":"2026-04-30T00:55:12.634Z","parentId":"a7b64